   1: # E4 analytic benchmark — the joint-normal fixed-threshold parity theorem
   2: 
   3: > The limiting-case theorem behind the numerical frontier. The full engine adds eligibility gates, heterogeneous
   4: > costs, greedy residual fill, MNAR reports, z-scoring, and credit — this theorem is the clean special case it
   5: > reduces to under stated assumptions. Regression: `scripts/simulation/e4-v5/theorem-check.mjs` (matches within
   6: > ~0.2 Monte-Carlo SE). Replaces the retired `β = 1−η` harm-weight law (which does not nest the v1.14 model).
   7: 
   8: ## Setup
   9: Candidate projects are i.i.d. draws of `(S, X)`, where `S` is true (mean-scale) value and `X` is a selector's
  10: signal (the central estimate `X_C = M^C`, or the distributed estimate `X_D = M^D`). Assume:
  11: 1. `(S, X)` is **jointly normal**, `Var(X) > 0`.
  12: 2. Equal costs, no eligibility gate, no credit; each selector funds the top fraction `q ∈ (0,1)` by its own `X`.
  13: 3. Selection is at the **population threshold** `t = μ_X + σ_X · z_q`, `z_q = Φ⁻¹(1−q)` (equivalently, the exact
  14:    top-`qK` quota in the `K → ∞` limit).
  15: 
  16: ## Lemma (expected selected value per candidate)
  17: ```
  18: V := E[S · 1{X > t}] = q·μ_S + φ(z_q) · Cov(S,X)/σ_X ,
  19: ```
  20: where `φ` is the standard normal pdf.
  21: 
  22: **Proof.** Joint normality gives the linear conditional mean `E[S | X = x] = μ_S + (Cov(S,X)/σ_X²)(x − μ_X)`. Then
  23: ```
  24: E[S·1{X>t}] = ∫_t^∞ E[S|X=x] f_X(x) dx
  25:             = μ_S·P(X>t) + (Cov(S,X)/σ_X²)·∫_t^∞ (x − μ_X) f_X(x) dx.
  26: ```
  27: `P(X>t) = q`, and the standard truncated-normal identity `∫_t^∞ (x − μ_X) f_X(x) dx = σ_X·φ(z_q)` give
  28: `V = q·μ_S + (Cov(S,X)/σ_X²)·σ_X·φ(z_q) = q·μ_S + φ(z_q)·Cov(S,X)/σ_X`. ∎
  29: 
  30: ## Parity condition
  31: For two selectors `X_C`, `X_D` at the same `q`, the common `q·μ_S` term and the common positive tail factor
  32: `φ(z_q)` cancel, so
  33: ```
  34: V_D = V_C   ⇔   Cov(S,X_D)/σ_{X_D} = Cov(S,X_C)/σ_{X_C}.
  35: ```
  36: **The parity boundary is the equality of the two signal-to-noise covariance ratios `Cov(S,X_k)/sd(X_k)`.** The
  37: intercept `a` of the central model is **absent** (rank-invariant under a fixed funded share with no gate); it
  38: re-enters only in the numerical model through the own-estimate eligibility gate and heterogeneous `/c_j`.
  39: 
  40: For the central signal `X_C = a + (b−w)·S + w·v_p + η` with a distinct project-varying projection `Z = v_p − S`
  41: (typed as its own variable, `η ⊥ (S, v_p)`):
  42: ```
  43: Cov(S,X_C) = b·Var(S) + w·Cov(S,Z),
  44: Var(X_C)   = b²·Var(S) + w²·Var(Z) + 2bw·Cov(S,Z) + Var(η).
  45: ```
  46: 
  47: ## Large-K corollary (link to the frozen estimand)
  48: The lemma is about expected selected sums, not automatically the frozen ratio-of-sums estimand. If
  49: `O_K/K → V_O > 0` (oracle LLN), the numerators `D_K/K, C_K/K` converge, and `Pr(O_K ≤ o_min) → 0`, then
  50: ```
  51: m_K = Σ(D_K − C_K)/Σ O_K  →  (V_D − V_C)/V_O ,
  52: ```
  53: so the covariance-ratio equality is the parity boundary **in the large-project limit**. Finite-world `m` is
  54: numerical; the engine's ratio-of-sums estimator is the finite-`K` object the lemma approximates.
  55: 
  56: ## Honest scope
  57: - The MNAR distributed signal is **not** exactly jointly normal at finite reach (thresholded non-response +
  58:   Bernoulli thinning); the Gaussian mapping is a **moment-matched reduced-form approximation**, not an identity.
  59:   So this lemma is the analytic sanity check, and the numerical frontier (with the true DGP) is the object.
  60: - `a` is deliberately absent from the benchmark frontier; do not read a benchmark magnitude off `a`.
   1: # E4 — draft paper section (EN; ES mirror on integration) — v2 anchored-scenario framing — DRAFT
   2: 
   3: > Rewritten to the author's anchored three-scenario framing. Resolves the rev-paper blockers: (1) reconciles with
   4: > the paper's own symmetry-gate NO-GO (Δ≈0.025) instead of contradicting it; (2) reports the actual numbers.
   5: > Source of numbers: `npm run e4:scenarios | e4:frontier | e4:evidence`; anchors in `research/e4-plausible-anchors.md`.
   6: > Framed as a comparative-institutions robustness result with anchored scenarios + a benchmark theorem, NOT a multiplier.
   7: 
   8: ## E4. When does coverage-routed selection beat central-proxy selection?
   9: 
  10: **Question.** At an equal budget and the same candidate projects, does coverage-routed distributed appraisal (Core
  11: v0) deliver more true social value than a competent central-proxy appraisal — and under exactly what conditions does
  12: each win? We answer with a mechanism model, a stylized benchmark theorem, and four **source-motivated declared scenarios** that level
  13: the field for both institutions.
  14: 
  15: **Mechanism.** True value splits into support and harm, `S = S⁺ − H` (mean scale). The central planner reads
  16: visible/salient value but is **myopic to harm, salience-gated**: harm-detection `b_H^C·s(V)` rises with a project's
  17: visibility `V`, so on the **low-visibility long tail** — the mass of public projects — it is nearly blind to
  18: concentrated opposition (oversight, opposition, comptroller reach mainly the visible, contested few). The
  19: distributed arm registers harm at weight `(1−β)` across the whole distribution. Under the declared salience-gating
  20: proxy (agenda-setting/salience — the load-bearing and least-empirically-pinned assumption), the aggregate advantage
  21: comes from the long tail: the projects that have no anti-value voice in the status quo.
  22: 
  23: **Model (matched budget; selection only).** `M^C = a + b·S⁺ + w·(v_{p,j}−S⁺) − b_H^C·s(V)·H + η` (project-varying
  24: `v_{p,j}` identifies `w`; form informed by elite-misperception evidence with an explicit political-opinion→project-
  25: value transport gap). The distributed estimate is a baseline-expanded, MNAR-biased mean of citizen reports. Both
  26: arms fund greedily under a shared budget; delivered value is scored on true `S`. Administrative-cost savings and
  27: corruption/leakage are separate, additive channels, deliberately excluded here.
  28: 
  29: **Stylized benchmark theorem.** Under joint normality and fixed-threshold selection, expected selected value per
  30: candidate is `V_k = q·μ_S + φ(z_q)·Cov(S,X_k)/sd(X_k)`, so parity ⇔ `Cov(S,X_D)/sd(X_D) = Cov(S,X_C)/sd(X_C)` (the
  31: intercept `a` is absent). This is a **stylized Gaussian fixed-threshold benchmark** (verified against simulation
  32: within ~0.2 Monte-Carlo SE); it nests the production harm-gated signal only under extra coefficient/gate
  33: restrictions, so it is a sanity-check limit, **not** a proof about the full engine (eligibility, heterogeneous
  34: costs, MNAR, credit) — which is the object.
  35: 
  36: **Four declared scenarios (level the field both ways).** Each knob's reference value is motivated empirically (public-
  37: procurement value is heavy-tailed — Skuhrovec et al. 2013, >40k Czech procurements, Zipf/Pareto — so most projects are
  38: low-visibility; participatory-budgeting turnout ≈1–3% informs participation as a joint moment), theoretically
  39: (agenda-setting/salience for harm myopia), or proxy-informed with a stated, **not-yet-propagated** transport gap
  40: (projection/bias). We are explicit that most magnitudes are declared reference/stress points, not target-domain
  41: calibrated bands (the CIs cover inner Monte-Carlo variability only). Reporting `m = D/O − C/O` (signed fraction of the
  42: full-information greedy benchmark, parity at 0) and each arm's delivered level `D/O`, `C/O`:
  43: 
  44: | scenario (assumptions) | m ± 95% CI | Core v0 | central | winner |
  45: |---|---|---|---|---|
  46: | **Central's full best plausible case** — low participation + competent, harm-aware, precise central | **−29.5%** [−29.9, −29.1] | 68% | 98% | **central** |
  47: | **No-myopia bundle** — probable + harm sight + unbiased + precise + no credit (NOT a myopia isolation) | **+6.1%** [5.8, 6.4] | 91% | 85% | ≈ parity |
  48: | **Harm-myopia only** — probable, changing ONLY the two harm-gate coordinates | **+30.4%** [29.9, 31.0] | 91% | 61% | Core v0 |
  49: | **Probable** — source-motivated reference | **+46.6%** [46.0, 47.4] | 91% | 45% | Core v0 |
  50: | **Distributed's favourable case** | **+199.8%** [197, 202] | 96% | −104% | Core v0 |
  51: 
  52: The field is genuinely level: **the central has a real winning region** — under its full best plausible case (low
  53: citizen participation and a competent, harm-aware central) it wins ~30% and delivers 98% of the benchmark. Core v0
  54: wins under the probable reference. The `D/O`/`C/O` split shows why: the central's delivered level swings 45%→85%→98%
  55: (and −104% when myopic on harmful projects), depending on whether it sees the anti-value and on participation.
  56: 
  57: **Reconciliation with the symmetry-gate NO-GO.** A pre-registered symmetry gate elsewhere reports a small pooled
  58: advantage (Δ≈0.025, below its rebuild threshold). That test **deliberately equips the central with competent,
  59: harm-aware appraisal** — the **no-myopia bundle** row above (+6.1%, same near-parity regime). Attribution is honest:
  60: turning off harm-myopia **alone** (only the two harm-gate coordinates) moves the probable advantage +46.6% → +30.4%
  61: — the harm channel accounts for **most, not all**, of it; the further drop to +6.1% is added central competence
  62: (unbiasedness, precision, no credit distortion), which the gate also assumes. The two results are the same
  63: phenomenon under opposite assumptions — a **qualitative reconciliation hypothesis** (different DGPs), not a
  64: reproduced limit.
  65: 
  66: **Where the frontier is.** Across five prespecified one-factor slices (`s_exp, b_H_C, p, beta, a_V`), none flips the
  67: winner from the probable scenario within its plotted range (a limited robustness statement over those five slices,
  68: not all parameters). Interpolating the full set of conditions from probable toward the central's best
  69: plausible case, the parity frontier is at **t ≈ 0.57** — reached **within** the plausible range, not beyond it. The
  70: winner therefore depends on where reality sits between the probable and central-favourable scenarios; `t` is an
  71: illustrative linear mix, not a calibrated competence scale.
  72: 
  73: **Honest limits.** (1) Central magnitudes are proxy-informed, not target-identified: the political-opinion→project-
  74: value transport is an assumption; only target-domain bridge data (planner forecasts, citizen value distributions)
  75: could shrink it. (2) The harm-myopia strength (`s_exp, b_H^C`) is theory-anchored (agenda-setting), the least
  76: empirically pinned knob and the crux. (3) `m>100%`/negative reflect legitimate value destruction (the losing arm
  77: funds net-harmful projects), read via `D/O`, `C/O`. (4) Cost and leakage channels are separate legs. E4 is a
  78: comparative-institutions robustness result with anchored scenarios + a benchmark theorem + a measurement plan —
  79: not an impact estimate.
  80: 
