  50: ### RESULTS — anchored scenarios (`npm run e4:scenarios`, N=1500,K=150, 800 worlds)
  51: > **CORRECTION (Codex v7):** the earlier "PRO-CENTRAL = +6.1%" conflated two distinct scenarios. Fixed. The
  52: > central's FULL best plausible case (every knob central-favourable) is `PRO_CENTRAL` in `scenario-configs.mjs`
  53: > (the single source of truth) and the CENTRAL WINS there. The +6.1% is a SEPARATE `NO_MYOPIA` scenario (myopia
  54: > isolated). Code now matches this table; a regression test pins the signs so they cannot fork again.
  55: 
  56: | scenario | m (gap) | 95% CI | Core v0 delivers | central delivers | winner |
  57: |---|---|---|---|---|---|
  58: | PRO-CENTRAL (central's full best plausible case) | **−29.5%** | [−29.9, −29.1] | 68% of oracle | 98% | **central** |
  59: | NO-MYOPIA (probable, but central sees harm — continuity anchor) | **+6.1%** | [5.8, 6.4] | 91% | 85% | ≈ parity |
  60: | PROBABLE (source-motivated reference) | **+46.6%** | [46.0, 47.4] | 91% | 45% | Core v0 |
  61: | PRO-DISTRIBUTED (favourable, moderate) | **+199.8%** | [197, 202] | 96% | −104% (destroys value) | Core v0 |
  62: 
  63: - **Level field (both ways):** the central has a genuine winning region — under its full best plausible case (low
  64:   participation + competent, harm-aware central) it wins ~30% and delivers 98% of the oracle. Core v0 wins under the
  65:   probable reference. The story from D/O: Core v0 is fairly robust (68–96%); the central swings 45%→85%→98% (or −104%
  66:   when myopic + harmful) — it depends on whether it sees the anti-value AND on citizen participation.
  67: - **Continuity / reconciliation with the NO-GO:** isolating harm-myopia (NO-MYOPIA: probable but central sees harm)
  68:   gives +6.1%, the same near-parity regime as the symmetry-gate ~2.5%. The +46% is the harm-myopia mechanism; the
  69:   gate deliberately equips the central with harm-aware appraisal, so the two results are the SAME phenomenon under
  70:   opposite assumptions — a qualitative reconciliation hypothesis, not a reproduced limit.
  71: 
  72: ### RESULTS — ceteris-paribus frontiers (`npm run e4:frontier`)
  73: - **Single-knob robustness:** from the PROBABLE scenario, NO single axis (`s_exp, b_H_C, p, beta, a_V`) crosses the
  74:   parity frontier within its plotted range — Core v0 wins throughout (+25% to +54%). The conclusion is robust to any
  75:   ONE assumption; reaching parity requires COMBINING central-favourable conditions.
  76: - **Combined scenario-path frontier (CORRECTED, Codex v7):** interpolating PROBABLE → the central's FULL best
  77:   plausible case (`PRO_CENTRAL`), m falls +47% → −30%; the **frontier (m=0) is at t ≈ 0.57** — i.e. conditions ~57%
  78:   of the way from probable toward the central's full best case flip the winner to the central. That is a PLAUSIBLE
  79:   region, NOT beyond-realistic (the earlier "t≈1.13 / beyond realistic" claim was wrong — it used a partial 8-knob
  80:   path). Honest headline: *the winner depends on where reality sits between the probable and the central-favourable
  81:   scenarios; no single knob decides it.* `t` is an illustrative linear mix, not a calibrated competence scale.
