  86: ## Anchored scenarios (author framing 2026-07-11) — level the field both ways
  87: Five named scenarios (values in `scenario-configs.mjs`), each a full config → `m ± 95% CI` (inner MC only):
  88: - **PRO-CENTRAL** — the central's FULL best plausible case (every knob central-favourable). The central WINS
  89:   (≈ −30%, delivers 98% of the benchmark). This is the honest "central's favourable region", NOT near-parity.
  90: - **MYOPIA-OFF** — PROBABLE with ONLY the two harm-gate coordinates changed. The genuine myopia-isolation contrast
  91:   (≈ +30%): attributes the harm channel ALONE (most, not all, of the probable advantage).
  92: - **NO-MYOPIA** — a harm-aware AND otherwise-competent central bundle (≈ +6%). The continuity anchor to the
  93:   symmetry-gate ~0.025 near-parity (that gate equips the central with competent harm-aware appraisal). NOT a myopia
  94:   isolation — it also improves projection/bias/noise/credit.
  95: - **PROBABLE** — source-motivated declared reference (≈ +46.6%), with the why/conditions.
  96: - **PRO-DISTRIBUTED** — favourable for distributed (≈ +200%; central destroys value).
  97: Per axis we also give: D_F range, ceteris-paribus frontier location, evidence for the probable value, result ± CI.
  98: 
  99: ### var #2 — `p` (participation) — ✅ CONFIRMED (author, 2026-07-11)
 100: - **Anchor type: E (empirical), with a mapping caveat.** Participatory-budgeting turnout (whole population) is low
 101:   single digits: San Francisco District 7 ~2,100/84,000 ≈ **2.5%** (Brennan Center); a ~280k city ~0.4–1.4%
 102:   (Signal Cleveland; PB Project). **Caveat:** in the model `p` is the reporting rate among the INTERESTED; reach `r`
 103:   already selects the interested subset, so PB turnout ≈ **reach × p**. With reach mean ≈0.13, a 1–3% turnout ⇒
 104:   `p ≈ 0.08–0.25`. → When reach (`a_r,b_r`) is anchored later, JOINTLY verify `reach × p ≈ 1–3%` (one observable
 105:   constrains two knobs).
 106: - **Proposed bands:** PRO-CENTRAL `p≈0.05` (sparse citizen signal); PROBABLE `p∈[0.08,0.25]`; PRO-DISTRIBUTED `p≈0.45`.
 107: - **Decision:** PENDING author confirmation.
 108: 
 109: ### var #1 — `a_V, b_V` (visibility tail shape) — ✅ CONFIRMED (author, 2026-07-11)
 110: - **Anchor type: E (empirical).** Public procurement value is heavy-tailed / power-law. Skuhrovec et al.,
 111:   *Exponential and power laws in public procurement markets* (arXiv:1309.0218): >40,000 Czech procurements 2006-2011,
 112:   power laws in revenues/spendings, top spenders follow Zipf (Pareto-like, heavy-tailed); reported exponent α≈1–1.24
 113:   (not verbatim-verified from abstract). Corroborated by IT-project cost power-law (arXiv:2210.01573). ⇒ a few large,
 114:   highly visible projects + a long tail of many small, low-visibility ones ⇒ `a_V < 1` (mass near low visibility) is
 115:   the PROBABLE case, reflecting real spending — not a convenient assumption. The Beta is a bounded stylized
 116:   approximation of the power law (do not overclaim an exponent fit).
 117: - **Proposed bands:** PRO-CENTRAL `a_V≈1.0` (lighter tail, more projects visible → oversight reaches them);
 118:   PROBABLE `a_V∈[0.3,0.8], b_V∈[2,5]` (heavy tail); PRO-DISTRIBUTED `a_V≈0.2` (very heavy tail).
 119: - **Caveat:** procurement VALUE proxies the size dimension of visibility, not visibility per se (controversy/media
 120:   also drive it); one-country study. Could add US/Chile corroboration later.
 121: - **Decision:** PENDING author confirmation of the bands.

